ache` to `False` to disable this behavior and ensure the\n            dependency is called again (if declared more than once) in the same request.\n            \"\"\"\n        ),\n    ] = True,\n) -> Any:\n    ...\n```\n\n### Explanation of Dependency Injection in FastAPI\n\n1. **Definition**: The `Depends` function allows you to declare dependencies for your path operations. You can pass a callable (like a function) that FastAPI will invoke to resolve the dependency.\n\n2. **Usage**: You typically use `Depends` in your route handlers to specify which dependencies are required. For example, in the provided context, the `get_item` function uses `Depends(get_username)` to inject the username dependency:\n\n   ```python\n   @app.get(\"/items/{item_id}\")\n   def get_item(item_id: str, username: str = Depends(get_username)):\n       ...\n   ```\n\n3. **Caching**: The `use_cache` parameter allows you to control whether the result of the dependency should be cached for the duration of the request. By default, it is set to `True`, meaning that if the same dependency is requested multiple times within the same request, the cached value will be used.\n\n4. **Error Handling**: If a dependency raises an exception, FastAPI will handle it appropriately, often converting it into an HTTP response. For example, in the `get_username` function, if an `OwnerError` is raised, it results in an HTTP 400 error.\n\n5. **Global Dependencies**: FastAPI also supports global dependencies that can be applied to all routes by passing them to the `FastAPI` constructor, as shown in the documentation examples.\n\nThis design pattern allows for clean, modular, and testable code, as dependencies can be easily mocked or overridden during testing, as demonstrated in the second context file (`tutorial001_py310.py`).\n\n\n**Sources (5):**\n1. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/docs_src/dependency_testing/tutorial001_py310.py` (lines 1-56) [score: 0.836]\n2. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/fastapi/param_function