n        data = await websocket.receive_text()\n        await websocket.send_text(f\"Message text was: {data}\")\n```\n- **Endpoint**: `/ws`\n- **Functionality**: Accepts a WebSocket connection and echoes back any text message received.\n\n### 2. **File: `tutorial002.py`**\nThis implementation adds authentication via a session cookie or token and allows for a query parameter.\n\n```python\n@app.websocket(\"/items/{item_id}/ws\")\nasync def websocket_endpoint(\n    websocket: WebSocket,\n    item_id: str,\n    q: Union[int, None] = None,\n    cookie_or_token: str = Depends(get_cookie_or_token),\n):\n    await websocket.accept()\n    while True:\n        data = await websocket.receive_text()\n        await websocket.send_text(\n            f\"Session cookie or query token value is: {cookie_or_token}\"\n        )\n        if q is not None:\n            await websocket.send_text(f\"Query parameter q is: {q}\")\n        await websocket.send_text(f\"Message text was: {data}, for item ID: {item_id}\")\n```\n- **Endpoint**: `/items/{item_id}/ws`\n- **Functionality**: Accepts a WebSocket connection, checks for a session cookie or token, and can also handle a query parameter. It sends back the session or token value, the query parameter (if provided), and echoes the received message along with the item ID.\n\n### 3. **File: `tutorial003.py` and `tutorial003_py39.py`**\nThese implementations utilize a `ConnectionManager` class to manage multiple WebSocket connections.\n\n```python\nclass ConnectionManager:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.active_connections: List[WebSocket] = []\n\n    async def connect(self, websocket: WebSocket):\n        await websocket.accept()\n        self.active_connections.append(websocket)\n\n    def disconnect(self, websocket: WebSocket):\n        self.active_connections.remove(websocket)\n\n    async def send_personal_message(self, message: str, websocket: WebSocket):\n        await websocket.send_text(message)\n\n    async def broadcast(self, message: str):\n        for connection in self.active_connections:\n            await connection.send_text(message)\n\n@app.websocket(\"/ws/{client_id}\")\nasync def websocket_endpoint(websocket: WebSocket, client_id: int):\n    await manager.connect(websocket)\n    try:\n        while True:\n            data = await websocket.receive_text()\n            await manager.send_personal_message(f\"You wrote: {data}\", websocket)\n            await manager.broadcast(f\"Client #{client_id} says: {data}\")\n    except WebSocketDisconnect:\n        manager.disconnect(websocket)\n        await manager.broadcast(f\"Client #{client_id} left the chat\")\n```\n- **Endpoint**: `/ws/{client_id}`\n- **Functionality**: Manages multiple connections, allowing for personal messages to be sent back to the sender and broadcasting messages to all connected clients. It handles disconnections gracefully.\n\n### Summary\nThe WebSocket implementations across these files demonstrate various levels of complexity, from simple echoing of messages to managing multiple connections with authentication and broadcasting capabilities. Each implementation serves different use cases, showcasing the flexibility of WebSocket handling in FastAPI.\n\n\n**Sources (5):**\n1. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/fastapi/exceptions.py` (lines 1-178) [score: 0.076]\n2. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/docs_src/websockets/tutorial003_py39.py` (lines 1-82) [score: 0.011]\n3. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/docs_src/websockets/tutorial001.py` (lines 1-52) [score: 0.009]\n4. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/docs_src/websockets/tutorial003.py` (lines 1-84) [score: 0.007]\n5. `/kaggle/working/data/fastapi/docs_src/websockets/tutorial002.py` (lines 1-92) [score: 0.004]\n\n   **Metrics:** 8.25s | 4120 tokens\n\n\n================================================================================\nFINAL PERFORMANCE STATISTICS\n================================================================================\n\n\n============================